        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">
        Fall of Faraday Future
        </h2>  
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
       Back in 2014, Chinese tech entrepreneur Jia Yueting, Faraday Future, promised a <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://www.theverge.com/2018/11/13/18088438/faraday-future-electric-cars-ev-news-layoffs-bankruptcy" target="_blank">smartphone on wheels</a>. The FF91, a futuristic electric SUV, claimed a 0-60 mph time of under 2.5 seconds and a range of over 370 miles. It was marketed as the "Tesla killer." Faraday did everything, dramatic reveals and big-name hires from Apple, BMW, and Tesla itself. They envisioned AI-powered co-pilots that learned your driving habits. 
          </p>
        </mj-text> 

        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/faraday-future-ff91-car-showcase.jpg" alt="Faraday Future FF 91 electric vehicle on display with people observing." href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
         <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>
            The Faraday Future FF 91 on display at a tech expo. Credits: Maurizio Pesce/Wikipedia</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
           They introduced "<a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://www.google.com/search?client=safari&rls=en&q=fardaay++%22Variable+Platform+Architecture%22%2C&ie=UTF-8&oe=UTF-8" target="_blank">Variable Platform Architecture</a>", a modular platform that could support sedans, SUVs, and even sports cars. However, when Faraday Future made its public debut in 2016, the cracks began to show. A highly publicized self-parking demo failed while live. Their proposed $1B factory in Nevada ultimately didn’t materialize. Battery materials and chip shortages plagued the FF91’s development. 
            </p>
            <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            With loose accounting practices and mismanaged funds, KPMG withdrew as their auditor, further unsettling suppliers and stakeholders. At one point, FF burned through $800M in just six months, without a single car. By 2019, Jia Yueting filed for personal bankruptcy. Jump to mid‑2025, and Faraday Future is still around, but barely. The FF91 finally delivered 16 units as of January 2025. 
            </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column> 
    </mj-section>


