        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">
        Modularity and its defects
        </h2>  
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
       In September 2013, Dutch designer and Design Academy Eindhoven graduate Dave Hakkens had a <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://startuptalky.com/google-project-ara-failure-case-study/" target="_blank">radical idea</a>. The idea was called <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://www.onearmy.earth/project/phonebloks" target="_blank">Phonebloks</a>, a modular smartphone that lets you swap out individual components instead of replacing the entire device. Each part, camera, battery, storage, and processor, would be a separate chip-like “block” that slides into a baseboard, or “endoskeleton.” 
          </p>
        </mj-text> 

        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/google-project-ara-modular-phone.jpg" alt="Hands holding a modular smartphone with customizable components and small display showing weather." href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
         <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>
            Google’s Project Ara - a modular smartphone designed for swappable parts and ultimate customization. Credits: onearmy.earth</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
           Motorola, then a Google subsidiary, picked up the idea under the name <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://youtu.be/PQqudiUdGuo?si=6zgiFccKNhHAhayu" target="_blank">Project Ara</a>. Backed by <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Google_ATAP" target="_blank">Google’s ATAP</a> team, they aimed to bring Phonebloks to market, starting at just $50 for a basic kit. The vision was to create an open hardware platform, just like Android is for software. However, getting swappable components to fit and function in a compact frame was an engineering nightmare. Even more challenging was getting large companies to cooperate. 
        </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          If Phonebloks had succeeded, it would have been a game-ender for many major brands. Google, to its recognition, gave it a shot. But Project Ara was eventually shelved in 2016. Still, had the idea been nurtured and matured, we might be living in a very different smartphone world. E-waste would be significantly lower, and a global hardware developer ecosystem could have flourished.
          </p>
         
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column> 
    </mj-section>
    <mj-section background-color="#ffffff" padding-bottom="4px">
      <mj-column>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">
        Holograms and headaches
        </h2>  
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
       The <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://www.theverge.com/2018/10/29/18027782/red-hydrogen-one-review-all-hype" target="_blank">Red Hydrogen One</a>, released in 2018 with a hefty $1,295 tag, promised some wildly futuristic features. Developed by Red Digital Cinema, its appeal was a "holographic" 4-View display, designed to show 3D content without the need for glasses. Red also promised a modular design, allowing users to attach high-end components, including a cinema-grade camera module, thereby transforming the device into a filmmaking tool.
          </p>
        </mj-text> 

        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/red-hydrogen-one-phone.jpg" alt="RED Hydrogen One smartphone with 3D display shown alongside a pair of anaglyph 3D glasses." href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
         <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>
            The RED Hydrogen One promised a revolution in mobile visuals with its holographic display and 3D tech. Credits: The Verge</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            But things quickly fell apart. The holographic display turned out to be more of a blurry, headache-inducing experience. Its camera was mediocre, the mobile was bulky, and its performance lagged far behind competitors. The much-hyped modular accessories, especially the camera module that Red fans were drooling over, never saw the light of day.
            </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
       Internally, Red pointed fingers at its original design manufacturer in China for subpar hardware and software integration. However, to the tech world, it seemed more like Red had over-promised, under-delivered, and <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://mashable.com/article/red-hydrogen-one-failure-stupid-explanation" target="_blank">passed the blame</a> when things went awry. The Hydrogen One became a colossal flop and was widely considered one of the worst tech products of 2018.
          </p>
         
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column> 
    </mj-section>

